                <div id="theory--wrapper">
                    <h5><span style="color: #FF842F;">THEORY </span></h5>
                    <p>

                        <h5>Materials required:</h5>

                        <ul>
                            <li>Battery (5V)</li>
                            <li>Two bulbs (5V)</li>
                            <li>Switch</li>
                            <li>Connecting wires</li>
                            <li>Battery holder (optional)</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h5>Procedure:</h5>

                        <p style="text-align: justify;">
                            1. Connect one end of the first bulb to the positive
                            terminal of the battery using a connecting wire.
                            <br>
                            2. Connect the other end of the first bulb to one
                            end of the second bulb using another connecting
                            wire.<br>
                            3. Connect the other end of the second bulb to the
                            negative terminal of the battery using another
                            connecting wire.<br>
                            4. Ensure that all connections are secure and the
                            circuit is properly closed.<br>
                            5. Turn on the switch and observe both bulbs
                            lighting up.<br>
                            6. Turn off the switch and observe both bulbs
                            turning off.
                        </p>

                        <h5>Explanation:</h5>
                        <p style="text-align: justify;">
                            In a series circuit, the components are connected
                            end to end, so the current has only one path to
                            follow. When the switch is turned on, the current
                            flows from the battery, through the first bulb, then
                            through the second bulb, and finally back to the
                            battery. Because the bulbs are connected in series,
                            the same current flows through both bulbs, causing
                            them to light up. However, since the voltage of the
                            battery is divided between the two bulbs, each bulb
                            receives only a fraction of the voltage, causing
                            them to be dimmer than in a single bulb circuit.
                            When the switch is turned off, the circuit is
                            broken, and the current stops flowing, causing both
                            bulbs to turn off.
                        </p>

                        <h5>Note</h5>

                        <p style="text-align: justify;">
                            It is important to follow proper safety guidelines
                            when working with electricity. Always ensure that
                            the circuit is properly closed before turning on the
                            switch, and avoid touching the battery or bulbs when
                            the circuit is in operation
                        </p>

